# RSTP Topology & Port Roles Lab

## Objective
Understand Rapid Spanning Tree Protocol (RSTP) behavior by identifying the root bridge, analyzing port roles/states, and manually configuring link types on interfaces.

## Requirements
- 4 × Cisco L2 IOU Switches  
- 6 × VPC  

## What You Will Do
- Identify the root bridge using CLI  
- Examine port roles and states on all switches  
- Compare RSTP behavior with traditional STP concepts  
- Analyze differences in root bridge selection  
- Determine port roles on non-root switches  
- Manually configure RSTP link types (edge, point-to-point)  
- Verify topology convergence and behavior  

## Tasks
1. Use CLI to determine the root bridge and port roles/states on the root switch  
2. Identify what appears different compared to standard STP and analyze why  
3. Determine port roles/states on all remaining switches and verify using CLI  
4. Manually configure correct RSTP link types on interfaces  
5. Analyze expected link type for specific interfaces (e.g., access ports like SW1 F0/24)  

## Expected Outcome
- Correct identification of root bridge  
- Proper understanding of RSTP port roles (Root, Designated, Alternate)  
- Faster convergence behavior compared to STP  
- Correct link type configuration (edge vs point-to-point)  
- Stable and loop-free topology  

## Lab Files
- IOU images available in the Google Drive link  
- Import images into PNETLab using the setup guide  
- Load the `.unl` file to access the lab topology  

## Note
Refer to the objective diagram inside the `.unl` file for detailed guidance.
